02_Calculating_Posterior_Distributions

Arthur M. Albuquerque

May 14, 2021

In this document, we will provide the rationale underlying the effect sizes used in our project. We will focus on the mortality outcome.

First, we will load the data and calculate the log-odds ratio of the RECOVERY trial and its corresponding prior. Then, we will calculate the posterior distributions in log-odds ratio scale. Lastly, we will derive the risk differences from these posterior distributions.

Log-odds ratio, then odds ratio, then risk difference

Our ultimate goal in this project is to report posterior distributions of risk difference (RD) for each subgroup. We will eventually compile multiple studies in our analyses and each have their own baseline risk (BR). Notably, RD is intrinsically related to BR. Therefore, different studies with distinct RDs are not comparable between each other.

To overcome this limitation regarding RD, we have decided to use a fixed BR for each subgroup. We will use the BR in the respective control group from the RECOVERY trial.

Doi et al. stated that RD should be derived from the odds ratio (OR). Thus, in combination with a fixed BR, we will calculate RDs from OR. Here is the formula provided by Doi et al., where \(R D\) is risk difference, \(B R\) is baseline risk from the control group (no-exposure) and \(O R\) is odds ratio.

\[R D=\frac{B R * \left(B R-1\right)* \left(O R-1\right)}{B R*O R-B R+1}\]

First, we will calculate the log-odds ratio for the RECOVERY trial and its corresponding prior in each subgroup.

logOR_recovery_not_using =

    n2i = total_control,

Calculating Posterior Distributions

Now, we will first calculate the posterior distributions from log-odds ratio. We will combine mean and variance from likelihood (RECOVERY) and prior in a conjugate normal analysis to get the posterior distributions (Spiegelhalter et al., 2004).

Assuming each prior is normal distributed

\[N(\theta,\sigma^2)\]

and so is the data (likelihood).

\[N(\hat{\theta},\hat{\sigma}^2)\] The mean and variance of the posterior distributions can be estimated by the following formulas:

  • Mean

\[\frac{\frac{\theta}{\sigma^2} + \frac{\hat\theta}{\hat\sigma^2}}{\frac{1}{\sigma^2}+\frac{1}{\hat\sigma^2}}\]

  • Variance

\[\frac{1}{\frac{1}{\sigma^2}+\frac{1}{\hat\sigma^2}}\]

We will first load custom functions. You can find these in the GitHub repository of this project.

## Load custom functions

# To generate normal conjugate posterior probabilities

source(here("final_analyses", "script", "functions", "analyses", # file path
            "conjugate_normal_posterior.R"))                     # file name

# To generate posterior probabilities with an evidence-based prior
# (it requires "conjugate_normal_posterior.R" )

source(here("final_analyses", "script", "functions", "analyses", # file path
            "normal_approximation_logOR.R"))                     # file name

# To generate posterior probabilities with multiple priors
# (it requires "conjugate_normal_posterior.R" )

source(here("final_analyses", "script", "functions", "analyses", # file path
            "logOR_normal_approximation_multiple_priors.R"))     # file name

# To compile all posteriors into a tibble

source(here("final_analyses", "script", "functions", "analyses", # file path
            "tibble_all_posteriors_logOR.R"))                      # file name

We also pre-planned to perform sensitivity analyses using different priors. In addition to the ones calculated above (hereafter, evidence-based priors), we will also generate posterior distributions using four extra priors: non-informative, skeptical, optimistic and pessimistic.

The non-informative and skeptical priors’ mean equals to \(0\) ( = log(1) ). The optimistic prior’s mean equals to \(-0.223\) ( = log(0.8) ). The pessimistic prior’s mean equals to \(0.223\) ( = log(1.25) ).

We decided to use log(0.8) as the mean for the optimistic prior because the RECOVERY trial was designed to be well-powered for 20% relative risk reduction. In turn, we used the symmetrical opposite from log(0.8) in the log scale for the pessimistic mean, which is log(1.25).

Of note, these priors are normal distributed, thus they are described by a mean and a variance. We also pre-planned to use the respective evidence-based prior’s variance for the variance in all other prior distributions, but the non-informative. Instead, the latter will have a variance of \(10,000\).

Now, let’s calculate the posterior distributions using these extra priors.

## Use of corticosteroids

Calculating risk difference

As mentioned before, we will use the formula provided by Doi et al. to calculate the risk difference (RD) from a fixed baseline risk (BR) and odds ratio (OR).

\[R D=\frac{B R * \left(B R-1\right)* \left(O R-1\right)}{B R*O R-B R+1}\]

In the sections before, we calculated the log-odds ratio for the RECOVEY trial and prior distributions in each subgroup. We then calculated the posterior distributions in the log-odds ratio scale.

Now, we will exponentiate these values to obtain the odds ratio for the posterior distributions. We will first get the data frames (wide format) from the section before and transform them into the long format.

## Use of corticosteroids

samples_posteriors_not_using_death %>% head() %>% flextable() %>% autofit()

Lastly, we will apply the formula mentioned above to calculate the corresponding risk difference for each odds ratio.

\[R D=\frac{B R * \left(B R-1\right)* \left(O R-1\right)}{B R*O R-B R+1}\]

As you can see, we have to set a fixed baseline risk (BR) to calculate the risk difference from odds ratio.

In this project, we are analyzing 2 different subgroups regarding use of corticosteroids: not using and using. We are also analyzing 3 different subgroups regarding respiratory support: simple oxygen only, non-invasive ventilation and invasive mechanical ventilation.

We have decided that we will use the BRs from the respective control group in the RECOVERY trial as our references. You can see these BRs below:

Subgroup Baseline Risk in Control Group (%)
Use of corticosteroids
Not using 34.6
Using 34.9
Respiratory support
Simple oxygen only 22.9
Non-invasive ventilation 42.2
Invasive mechanical 50.7

Let’s apply the formula from Doi et al., 2020 to derive the posterior distributions in the risk difference scale.

# BR = Baseline Risk
# OR = Odds Ratio

RD_fun = function(BR,OR)
  {
( BR*(BR-1)*(OR-1) ) / ( BR*OR - BR+1)
}
# Calculating the risk differences

### Use of corticosteroids

## Not using

# Define baseline risk
BR_not_using = d2 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",
           corticosteroids == 0, # Not using
           outcome == "mortality") %>% 
      summarise(n = events_control/total_control) %>%
      pull()

samples_posteriors_not_using_death = 
  samples_posteriors_not_using_death %>% 
  # Apply formula from Doi et al., 2020
  mutate(RD = RD_fun(BR_not_using,
                     OR))

## Using

# Define baseline risk
BR_using = d2 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",
           corticosteroids == 1, # Using
           outcome == "mortality") %>% 
      summarise(n = events_control/total_control) %>%
      pull()

samples_posteriors_using_death = 
  samples_posteriors_using_death %>% 
  # Apply formula from Doi et al., 2020
  mutate(RD = RD_fun(BR_using,
                     OR))

### Respiratory support

## Simple oxygen

# Define baseline risk
BR_simple = d1 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",
           oxygen == "simple oxygen",
           outcome == "mortality") %>% 
      summarise(n = events_control/total_control) %>% 
      pull()

samples_posteriors_simple_death = 
  samples_posteriors_simple_death %>% 
  # Apply formula from Doi et al., 2020
  mutate(RD = RD_fun(BR_simple,
                     OR))

## Non-invasive

# Define baseline risk
BR_noninvasive = d1 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",
           oxygen == "non-invasive ventilation",
           outcome == "mortality") %>% 
      summarise(n = events_control/total_control) %>% 
      pull()

samples_posteriors_noninvasive_death = 
  samples_posteriors_noninvasive_death %>% 
  # Apply formula from Doi et al., 2020
  mutate(RD = RD_fun(BR_noninvasive,
                     OR))

## Invasive mechanical ventilation

# Define baseline risk
BR_invasive = d1 %>% 
    filter(trial == "RECOVERY",
           oxygen == "invasive ventilation",
           outcome == "mortality") %>% 
      summarise(n = events_control/total_control) %>% 
      pull()

samples_posteriors_invasive_death = 
  samples_posteriors_invasive_death %>% 
  # Apply formula from Doi et al., 2020
  mutate(RD = RD_fun(BR_invasive,
                     OR))

Plotting

To display some of our calculations, we will now plot the posterior distributions for log-odds ratio, odds ratio and risk difference for a single subgroup (not using corticosteroids).

We note that log-odds ratios less than \(0\), odds-ratios less than \(1\) and risk differences larger than \(0\) mean benefit for the mortality outcome.
